                <head>28. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On May 25, 1961, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> signed a
                    memorandum to President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName>
                    suggesting that he inform Chairman <persName corresp="#p_KNS2"
                        >Khrushchev</persName>, during their Vienna meeting, that the United States
                    proposed to install a direct telephone connection between the Department of
                    State and the Embassy in Moscow. An attached memorandum from <persName
                        corresp="#p_MCJJ1">John McCloy</persName> to Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> indicated that the proposal resulted from
                    the work of a panel that “recently studied measures to reduce the risk of war by
                    miscalculation.” A memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_MGGC2"
                        >McGhee</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName>
                    identified the panel as one convened by <persName corresp="#p_MCJJ1"
                        >McCloy</persName> and headed by Thomas Schelling of Harvard University.
                        <persName corresp="#p_MGGC2">McGhee</persName> noted that President
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> and Chairman <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName> did not discuss the telephone link.
                    These memoranda are in Department of State, <gloss target="#t_SP1">S/P</gloss>
                    Files: Lot 70 D 199, <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>. Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>’s May 25 memorandum is printed in <ref
                        target="frus1961-63v05#d53">volume V, Document 53</ref>.</p>
            </div>
